TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Empirical Test of Gain-Loss Separability in Prospect Theory
AU  - Wu, George
AU  - Markle, Alex B.
Y1  - 2008/07/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1070.0846
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1070.0846
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1322
EP  - 1335
VL  - 54
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We investigate a basic premise of prospect theory: that the valuation of gains and losses is separable. In prospect theory, gain-loss separability implies that a mixed gamble is valued by summing the valuations of the gain and loss portions of that gamble. Two experimental studies demonstrate a systematic violation of the double-matching axiom, an axiom that is necessary for gain-loss separability. We document a reversal between preferences for mixed gambles and the associated gain and loss gambles?mixed gamble A is preferred to mixed gamble B, but the gain and loss portions of B are preferred to the gain and loss portions of A. The observed choice patterns are consistent with a process in which individuals are less sensitive to probability differences when choosing among mixed gambles than when choosing among either gain or loss gambles.
AB  - We investigate a basic premise of prospect theory: that the valuation of gains and losses is separable. In prospect theory, gain-loss separability implies that a mixed gamble is valued by summing the valuations of the gain and loss portions of that gamble. Two experimental studies demonstrate a systematic violation of the double-matching axiom, an axiom that is necessary for gain-loss separability. We document a reversal between preferences for mixed gambles and the associated gain and loss gambles?mixed gamble A is preferred to mixed gamble B, but the gain and loss portions of B are preferred to the gain and loss portions of A. The observed choice patterns are consistent with a process in which individuals are less sensitive to probability differences when choosing among mixed gambles than when choosing among either gain or loss gambles.
